  "slug": "a-self-forgiveness-ritual",
  "title": "A Self-Forgiveness Ritual",
  "subtitle": "A twenty-minute writing ritual for forgiving yourself for something you are still carrying",
  "excerpt": "A twenty-minute ritual for the thing you keep returning to: what you did, what you wish had happened instead, and the work of putting it down. Uses writing and a physical release step.",
  "type": "PRACTICE",
  "sourceNotes": "Original to homemade.education. The use of writing as a forgiveness tool is documented in published psychological research on expressive writing and therapeutic ritual.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A twenty-minute ritual for the thing you have explained and re-explained to yourself and still carry. This is not for new pain. It is for the thing you understand but have not yet put down.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "What you need",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Two sheets of paper and a pen",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Twenty minutes of privacy",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "A quiet place to sit",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The ritual",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Step 1: Name it (five minutes)",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "On the first sheet of paper, write what you are forgiving yourself for. Name it specifically, without softening. Not \"I was a bad friend\" but what you actually did, on what day, and what the consequence was. Write it as plainly as you can.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Step 2: The other side (five minutes)",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "On the second sheet, write what you would say to a close friend who told you they had done the same thing. Write it to them, not to yourself. What would you want them to understand? What would you want them to stop carrying?",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Step 3: Read both back (five minutes)",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Read the first sheet. Then read the second. Notice where the distance is between how you treat yourself and how you would treat the friend. You do not have to resolve the distance today. Simply notice it.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Step 4: The release",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "At the bottom of the second sheet, write: \"I am forgiving myself for this. I am still allowed to be here.\"",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Then tear the first sheet in half. Discard it.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Step 5: Close (five minutes)",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Sit for five minutes with no input. No phone, no music. Let the practice settle. Keep the second sheet if you want it. Discard it if you don't.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this practice comes from",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Original to homemade.education. James Pennebaker's research shows that writing things down helps people put them down.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
